Solution__c:
JHF email July 13/16:  "This email is a response to issue 2 from your Beta test FX80 at Rite AID Hanover, PA:
       "2.       Analog Inputs on the NRIOs were bouncing around.  At first, we caught one of the NRIOs was not grounded, but it still exhibited this behavior after the ground was applied.  Chris indicated he did not have this bouncing using the NDIO and the points were still set to slow within the Proxy."

I logged into this site using the IP information you forwarded, but was not immediately able to observe any "bouncing"; the point histories I looked at didn't seem to contain any obvious non-linearities, either.   Can you suggest some points to look at which exhibit these symptoms?

In the absence of any other information, my strongest hunch at this point is that this is a noise issue associated either with ...
     * one or more of the UI connections to the NRIO (see attached Niagara Central article 7817), and/or ...
     * the NRIO bus

As Martin has already suggested, it would be good to have a detailed termination diagram to refer to; I would be looking primarily for mis-grounding issues, as well as possible cross-feed of voltages from multiple sources (for example, between the power supply feeding the FX80, the NRIO and any secondary power supplies for active sensors (e.g. 0-10vdc, 4-20mA) connected to the NRIO UIs.

I would also be helpful to have answers to the questions posed in the diagram below;  will stand by for your responses.
    FX80 COM port:  1 or 2?   
    EOL jumper setting:  END?  BIA?  MID?

    RS485 NRIO bus segment:
       * how many devices in all?
       * total length?
       * shielded wire?  shield drain hard grounded in only one location?

    What point types are affected by "bouncing" values...
       *UIs with resistive sensors?
       * UIs with voltage type sensors?
       * UIs with current type sensors?
        
 
If we cannot isolate a physical reason for this "bouncing", Martin Stoppel offers a programmatic workaround that would filter out momentary glitches in the UI values ... please see attached "filter.bog" and "Filter bog file info.doc".
Subject: Beta test: FX80 at Rite AID Hanover, PA  ... please assign immediately to John Franz

JHF email Aug 22/16:  "Our Field Liaison Engineer for PCT and I have done some extensive testing with your CAF file and he was able to devise a test sequence that causes the application to consistently transition to Supplemental Heating first (per your System Selection Wizard choice):
When you start your simulation, do the following:
Set the box to occupied.
Play with the velocity pressure to get the damper to a position other than 0 or 100.
Set your velocity pressure input to .04 (~196CFM)(this should satisfy and stabilize the damper output).
Decrease your zone temperature and see if the heating sequences correctly.

Based on this finding, I took a closer look at the Occupied Zone Sequencing (VAV) HFR finite state machine and identified a condition where the FSM will transition to Box Heating first, even if Supplemental Heating is selected as the primary heating source (see attached "Occupied Zone Sequencing (VAV) HFR marked up.PNG").   It appears that the current DPR-O command must be >0% and

Solution__c:
JHF email Sept 21/16: "The standard chiller application is intended to rotate the chillers either based on starts or runtime.  Reselection of the current device(s) occurs as the load fluctuates, i.e. the expectation is that the current stage will switch off naturally as the load drops and then a new stage (which has either a lower number of starts or lower run hours) will be selected when the load increases again.  One drawback of this approach is that if the load is stable, the current stage will run indefinitely.

If you want to keep the standard PCT control sequence,  you can manually force reselection of the current load *right now* by following this three-step sequence:
    Step 1 .. manually command "Rotate Now" to true
    Step 2 .. artificially drop the load to zero (this could be done by temporarily overriding either the Process Variable value or the Setpoint to make them equal); wait for all stages to drop out
    Step 3 .. release your override to Process Variable or Setpoint; as the MSC stages up, it should select the stages with lower number of starts or lower runtime

If the above is not satisfactory, the alternative would be to build a custom sequencing activity, possibly using the Global Sequencer, to yield the sequence of operation desired by your customer."
Subject: Chiller Rotation

JHF email Sept 24/16:  "I have opened case HD 00041778 for the issue you describe below.  Your case will go into our call handling queue and will be addressed, in the order it was received, by the first available agent (which may or may not be me). 
In the future, if you are reporting a new issue, I would request that you either contact our Level 1 call handlers at 1-800-275-5676 or  email to PSOTechSupport@jci.com.

In the meantime, here are some known reasons for MSTP communication unreliability:
   
   1) Improper tuning policies assigned to your MSTP points ... for details, please see the attached solution database article 30212 and its collateral documents 
            [BACnet setup for large networks with FX PC controllers.doc and Creating a new tuning policy for specific points.doc]


   2) Bus is excessively busy ... for each affected MSTP network, what is the bus busy time? (from your BACnet property sheet)..


   3) JAR file corruption in the FX Supervisory controller ... in some cases, the JAR files relating to a particular program feature may be missing, corrupted or out-of-date.  Can you advise..
       * what version of Wb/AX (or Wb/N4) is your FX Supervisory controller at? 
       * what patches are loaded?
       * do the JAR file sizes in your FX Supervisory controller  match the corresponding JAR file sizes in your FX Wb of the same version
           when viewed in File Transfer Client?  (if not, recopy the affected JAR files using File Transfer Client)
   

   4) Baud rate is too fast for this installation ... faster baud rates (e.g. 76.8k baud) make a bus more susceptible to noise.  
                Are you seeing "DCMD_MSTP_TX_FRAME" errors in the Application Director?  If so, it may be possible to eliminate some of these by dropping to a slower baud rate.


   5) Mixed baud rates ... please ensure that all of the controllers on the affected bus(ses) are running at the correct baud rate.  If you have any field controllers on this bus that are "auto baud", it may be necessary to power cycle them so they can re-learn the correct baud rate.


   6) Noise on the MSTP bus ... typically caused by improper configuration or installation issues; 
             for the each affected MSTP network can you advise:
       * how long is the bus run? 
                    (RS485 spec is 4000 feet max) 
                         * is it wired using the recommended 24AWG 3-conductor twisted and shielded cabling?
       * is the shield continuous and grounded only at a single point?
       * how many total devices are on this bus?
               (JCI spec is 64 max)
       * what is the device mix..
             - how many FX-PC (or MS-FEC)?
             - how many Legacy FX?
             - how many TEC2000-series?
             - how many TEC3000-series?
             - how many (and what brand/model) 3rd-party?
       * how many repeaters are on this bus?
       * how many devices are on each bus segment? 
            (RS485 spec is 32 max)

   7) Duplicate BACnet Network IDs and/or duplicate BACnet Device IDs on other segments of the BACnet internetwork that this FX Supervisory controller is connected to;
             to test for this possibility, isolate each affected MSTP bus by either...
             * turning off BACnet routing inside the FX Supervisory controller, or
             * physically disconnecting the FX Supervisory controller from any other BACnet segments

If the above suggestions do not yield a solution, it may be necessary to get a PilotFish data capture of  MSTP network traffic for further analysis."
Subject: FX Supv controller MSTP comm problems

As of November, 2005 the FA-DX9100-8454 and the FA-DX9100-7454 (repair) have been discontinued.

Solution__c:
Modernization Guide for N2 Controllers - Metasys,Â LIT-12012005:
Downloading and Commissioning
Legacy N2 controllers support local application downloading and commissioning using the appropriate programmingÂ and commissioning tool hosted on a computer (for example, HVACPro or GX Tool), the computer's serial interface,Â and an RS-232 to RS-485 adapter (for example, the MM-CVT or IU-9100 or Zone Bus adapter).
FEC controllers also support local downloading and commissioning; however, they require a different technology.Â For local downloading and commissioning, FEC controllers require that CCT is hosted on a computer with a BluetoothÂ interface or a third-party Bluetooth interface, and that a BTCVT Bluetooth Commissioning Converter is connectedÂ to the FEC controller's SA Bus.
NCM and NAE Series supervisory devices contain a feature called Passthrough, which enables you to remotelyÂ download and commission legacy N2 controllers. NCM and NAE Passthrough do not support N2-configured FECÂ controllers. When you use an FEC controller to replace a legacy N2 controller that is supervised by an NCM or NAE,Â you lose the capability to use Passthrough to remotely download and commission the N2-configured controller. YouÂ and your customers need to be aware that programming and commissioning the N2-configured FEC controller mustÂ be performed onsite with access to the FEC controller's SA bus connection.


N2 Integration with the NAE Technical Bulletin,Â LIT-1201683:
Switchable Communications Protocols
The N2 capable FEC controllers:
â¢ Â  Â do not support Zone BusÂ 
â¢ Â  Â do not support a wireless connection to the N2 bus
â¢ Â  Â do not support NxE passthru


Article ID: 31741
Problem:
Can Passthru be used with a VMA1832?Â 
Solution:
No. CCT is unable to connect to an NxE and communicate on the N2 trunk.Â 
Â The VMA1832 (when N2 enabled) requires the BT-CVT connected to the SA Bus for downloads and Commissioning with CCT.
Â The VMA1832 is no longer being shipped with N2 communication enabled by default January 1, 2016
Â This information also applies to all FEC, FAC, and VMA16xx devices once switched to N2 mode
Â If a VMA1832 is converted in CCT to function with MSTP communications passthru would also be enabled. The passthru limitation is due to the N2 environment not the Hardware used in the controller.Â 


Article ID: 33708
Applies to (product revision/patch):
FEC, VMA, and FAC Controllers converted to use N2 communicationsÂ 
Problem:
How can an N2 converted FxC Family device be commissioned if Bluetooth is not allowed?Â 
Cause:
CCT does not have the ability to function in a passthru mode on an N2 trunk. Quite frankly the size of the Main Code for these devices would take a very long time being transferred at 9600 baud.Â 
Solution:
This solution is tagged for JCI Employees only.
Â No solution is available.Â

If brownouts, power outages, or blips are a concern, it is highly recommended to install a UPS on Supervisory Device panels to prevent shutdowns & offline alarms, otherwise premature failure of the engine's battery may occur.

SDB Article #s 5037 & 5617

Metasys SMP Help,Â LIT-1201793:
Table 101: Engine Device Object Attributes - Focus/Configuration Tab
Power ConsecutiveÂ Sample-
Specifies the number of consecutive AC line status samples (indicate a power loss)
must be received before the device concludes that a power failure has occurred. When
the device concludes that power has failed, the device begins an orderly shutdown
process. The process used for determining whether a power failure has occurred
protects the device from shutting down during short power failures or certain brownout
conditions. Using default values, a power failure of less than 5 seconds does not prompt
a device shutdown.

Power SamplingÂ Interval-
Specifies the period at which the AC line status is sampled to determine whether a
power failure has occurred. This attribute is used in conjunction with the Power
Consecutive Samples attribute.

If you change or converted the states text on EMERGENCY button point, could use the Safety Input 4 & not have to customize module at all.Â

Solution__c:
If NC-3 will be replaced then N1 migration will come back, else need to edit the NIE's Discovery IP, Gate, Node to be another NCM.

SDB 6186:
1) Ensure that the node address of an NIE is higher than the node address of the NCMs and OWSs on the N1 network to avoid the possibility of the NIE becoming the lowest node address after node addresses are taken offline. If that occurs the higher addressed NCMs and OWSs can think the NIE is a Node Master. The NIE cannot participate in the N1 network as a Node Master.
2) The Discovery Node is always an NCM (not an OWS) and the NCM is NOT the Node Manager.

SDB 5159:
2) Make sure the NIEs on the N1 network are defined in the Global.ddl file as PCs with the assigned gate/node and IP address.Â 
3) DDL and re-download the global file.
Subject: N1 integration offline

Article ID: 34177

Problem:
FYI-921 You may be receiving numerous new alarms after installing or upgrading to Metasys 8.0.Â 
Cause:
A number of new alarm extensions were incorporated into the NAE with release 8.0 as a result of enhancement request CR53652. Since the release of 8.0, the FSC has received reports from the field regarding these alarms. All 8 of the new alarms are enabled by default.
Solution:
Each of these alarms serves a specific purpose and those purposes should be evaluated concerning the practicality of alarming:
COV Rcv Rate: Monitors the rate at which the NAE is receiving COV notifications from all BACnet (MS/TP and IP) integrations. High alarm limit defaults to 350 per minute. Differential defaults to 150 per minute.
The COV Rcv Rate alarm is covered in detail in Article 33925.

Solution__c:
Things to consider prior to shutting down the North Pavilion ADX:
1. All NxE's should be uploaded to SCT and backups made.
2. A computer or laptop should be kept by UAB personel that has SCT, HVACPro and CCT on it for system maintenance, pass though etc.
3. Verify the effect that this could have on the CAMS network. Â Matrikon runs on the ADX, shutting down the server will effectively shut down CAMS reporting from the North Pavilion.

To change the BACOID's and IP's of the NxE's:

1. Using the uploading SCT backup from above, make a back up and store it in a safe place.
2. In SCT change the BACOID's of the engines and IP addresses as directed by UAB.
3. Download from SCT to each engine using the device change screen and option in SCT to download the changes. Clarify with the customer the affect this may have on evironmental systems (OR's, etc.) prior to the download. Â Consider the time it takes to download, the engine reboot, restart and control processes to execute. Â Also plan time to locate the engine and download it locally if the download via the network fails.
4. Once all engines are updated and operation is verified, upload each again, make a back up and store it in a safe place.
Subject: Customer specific questions regarding North Pavilion Hospital ADX

Solution__c:
Starting at Metasys Release 4.0, the UI has some changes regarding the ability to command objects in the FEC Family of Controllers. You will be offered only the commands available for that object.

For example, an object where you can only change the Relinquish Default value, you will only be offered to change the default value. Typically, these are objects not defined as Network Inputs in CCT. For objects you can adjust from a supervisory controller, you will be offered Adjust, Operator Override, Release Operator Override, Release, and Release All. Typically, these are objects which are defined as network inputs or physical inputs and outputs in CCT.

Metasys User Interface (UI) Enhancements

As part of this new Metasys release, Release 2.1 of the Metasys UI introduces a new Graphics Package and Editor that provide for improved system visualization, faster troubleshooting, and more efficient graphics management.

  • The Graphics Package lets Metasys system designers efficiently create, edit, and manage graphics in either Metasys UI or Metasys UI Offline.
  • The Graphics Editor does not require any additional software. Metasys system designers can create and edit a graphic within the Metasys UI and validate it immediately.
  • The Graphics Editor includes a full library of symbols and templates that provide photo-realistic images of equipment, systems, and floor plans as a starting point for system designers who do not have the time or expertise to create graphics from scratch.
  • New features include auto-binding, single-source master layer editing, and symbol show and hide based on equipment configuration.
  • Annotations when commanding is now available to allow Metasys operators to add annotations or a reason behind a particular command action. They can view these notes in the Equipment Activity widget.

Solution__c:
Reset/reboot the NCE25/NAE35/45 and attempt the SCT upload operation again.

Additional workarounds:
  • 1) Do not download the security database into the NCE25/NAE35/45 if it contains a large number of users. Try to limit the security database in the NCE25/NAE35/45 to 10 or fewer users. After the reduced security database has been redownloaded into the NCE25/NAE35/45 attempt the upload again.
    2) Keep the security database in the ADX/S, leaving the default usernames and passwords in the NCE25/NAE35/45.
        NOTE: If the Supervisory Device does not respond to the above workarounds, locate a known working and correct database. Run an NAE/NIE Update Tool (NUT) operation on the engine. Select Extended in the target (this will completely re-write the flash on the engine), and an update process type of PXE Only. After the NUT operation completes, redownload the supervisory device using SCT and the known working and correct database, then, retry another upload.

Solution__c:
Article ID: 32825

Applies to (product revision/patch):
N2 capable FEC, FAC or VMA devicesÂ 
Problem:
How do I set the address of an N2 FxC device above 127?Â 
Solution:
As outlined in the Modernization Guide for N2 Controllers - Metasys, LIT-12012005, at http://cgproducts.johnsoncontrols.com/met_pdf/12012005.pdf, the following steps must be taken to set the address of an N2 capable FxC to 128 or higher:
1) Disconnect the 24 VAC power supply from the controller.
2) Remove the FC Bus (N2) connector from the controller.
3) Set the address DIP switch to the desired N2 address.
4) Set the 128 DIP switch to OFF.
5) Reconnect the 24 VAC power supply to the controller.
6) Using CCT and the Wireless Commissioning Converter (BTCVT) connected to the SA Bus of the controller, download the firmware and the N2 configured application configured for the dip switch address set in Step 4 (desired address -128). The download process will prompt you to confirm switching the communication protocol to N2.
7) Click OK to accept.
8) After the download has completed, disconnect the 24 VAC power supply from the controller.
9) Set the 128 DIP switch to ON.
10) Reattach the FC Bus (N2) connector to the controller.
11) Reconnect the 24 VAC power supply to the controller.Â 
NOTE: CCT allows addresses >127 to be configured when the N2 Mapping table is populated. If the N2 Mapping table is not populated, the 4-127 address rules are enforced.
NOTE: Once a controller is N2 enabled, subsequent downloads may be performed with CCT configured for addresses >127 as the wireless function of the 128 dip switch is disabled in N2 mode.Â 
Â

SDB Article # 20951:Â 
The NAE UI is updated based on the COV Increment, but the values are passed to the controller. You can see this in the priority array of the Analog Value at the NAE, and in CCT commissioning.

For building static pressure and other small readings, this may appear to not work very well. To refresh the value at the UI, close and open the object in the Focus Window, which forces it to read the current value.

To ensure best performance inside the FEC, be sure to set the inputÂ 'Use COV Min Send Time' to True.
Suggest exposing only the master point for users, they don't need to see the slave point, you know the value is still being written into the controller.
Otherwise you have to multiply it out to a higher #, then divide it back in CCT & expose a network output as an effective value.

Solution__c:
The MSTP F/C bus requires an active network to bias the RS-485 bus properly at the communication rates being used. A fixed resistor would load the network and not allow full communications at the high rates being used on the MSTP bus.

The MSTP bus repeaters also have active biasing to allow the maximum bus length and number of devices specified for the FC bus. Setting the EOL switches on the repeater provides the same biasing as the controllers or BACEOL device.

Biasing provided by the EOL device is not required on the SA bus because the maximum wire length and number of devices a minimized and the bus master (VMA or FEC) provides the proper biasing.
Subject: What's the EOL resistance of our FC bus?

The NAE does not appear in the All Items tree beneath the Metasys Site Object and folders.
Â 
New, out-of-the-box NAE after initial login and password change displays an empty All Items tree. There is no NAE, so no interaction with the engine can take place.Â 
Error Message:
Cause:
Some new engines that have been configured with hostname and IP address exhibit this issue after a device reset.
Â 
The cause of this issue is unknown for new engines out of the box although it appears to indicate a corrupt archive.moi within the engine itself.
Â 
For engines that exhibit this issue after configuration and device reset, the issue is with how the WES 7 operating system in NAE55xx-3 engines handles static IP addresses configured within the APIPA (169.254.x.x) address range.Â 
Solution:
There is no solution at this time.
Â 
In some cases the issue may be worked around by re-imaging the engine via the NUT.
Â 
For NAE55xx-3 engines that appeared fine out of the box and lost the device object after a reset, the problem may be prevented by never configuring the engine with a static IP address in the APIPA (169.254.x.x) range. Â 

Notes for BE employees:
If a re-image of the engine fails to correct the issue, the engine should be returned via the standard RMA process. A FAR report should be requested with the RMA providing the engine remains under warranty.

Solution__c:
If the certificate that is currently bound is an MD5 hash, you should remove the binding and let the install create a new one.

f the existing certificate's hash algorithm is SHA256, and bound to the default website, continue with the Metasys Server install / upgrade.
Â 
If thereÂ is no bound certificate, and the site wants to use a self signed certificate, proceed with the install / upgrade, as it will create a SHA256 self signed certificate.
Â 
If the existing certificate is a self signed non SHA256, unbind the certificate from the default website in the IIS Manager panel (See SDB Article 33715) and continue with the install / upgrade and a SHA256 self signed certificate will be generated
Â 
If the existing certificate is a purchased certificate, and not SHA256, the site will need to upgrade their certificate or purchase a new certificate that uses the SHA256 hash algorithm, and bind that to the default website before MUI will be able to be used. The install or upgradeÂ can beÂ completed as expected, and the Metasys Server SMP will operate normally, MUI is the only thing that relies on the hash algorithm being SHA256. The SHA256 certificate can be bound to the default website after the fact, and then MUI should work as expected.

Solution__c:
USB stick to hardwire PC to trunk, or add Lon-IP router. Many from Loytec or Echelon will work, JCI offers Echelon iLon600 in PFM catalog. PN# 72601 for 120vac model, PN# 72603 for 24vac model. Best practice is to place it in panel with NAE that it serves.

Install LN-Builder on customer machine. All Plug-ins, updates, upgrades must be downloaded on JCI laptop using SmartInstaller, then setup files manually transferred to customer machine.
Using the Control Panel> LonWorks Interfaces (OpenLDV) utility, add an Ethernet network interface to the PC.
Run the Echelon IP-852 Configuration Server, setup the PC as the 'Config Server', then add both the PC & iLon as child devices on the new IP-852 channel. This program must be running at all times in order for LN-Builder to communicate to the router.
In the LN-Builder, open the database OffNet (not connected).
Add a channel using type: IP-10L.
Add a router with near side as the IP channel & far side as the FT-10 channel.
Right-click on the Network Interface & Change Channel from FT-10 to IP.
Close & re-open database using the Ethernet network intaerface.

Applies to (product revision/patch):
LN-VAVLF-1 LN-VAVLF-2Â 
Problem:
What is the difference between the LON templates for the LN-VAVLF-1 and LN-VAVLF-2?Â 
Solution:
There is no difference between the LN-VAVLF-1 and LN-VAVLF-2 LON templates. These controllers use the same template.Â 

Also because the XIF and Program ID didn't change, they use the same Plug-ins.

To create a monitor only point, go ahead & configure it in the plug-in as something binary & choose desired SNVT, Apply. Then set it back to Unused, Apply, so that it doesn't mess with application. You can still map the NV.## to Metasys & monitor the point.

For LN-VAVCF, start with a standard application from the Code Library (Project Files) & modify as needed. Can add other snippets that are available too (Custom blocks, CO2 Control).
Subject: What is the correct plug-in to use with LN-VAVLF-2?

1. [Can the] FX Server (version 14.x) .. be installed in a Virtual Environment ?Â

Â  Â JHF: Yes ... please note, however, that Niagara Network discovery does not work across routers, so the Niagara devices would have to Â be manually mapped to each other in this scenario.


3. And in this case, if the FX-Server also would be able to discover and operate different Bacnet IP devices using different subnet IP addressÂ

Â  Â  Â  - the FX Server will need to be licensed for the required number of "IP" devices/points
Â  Â  Â  - routing between the subnets must support the selected BACnet/IP UDP port (default 47808) Â  Â

You clarified that the "existing 2 wires" refers to wiring runs from the VAV box location down to the existing room sensor location. Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â * reduce the number of mapped points for that bus
Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â * reduce the number of mapped controllers for that busÂ 


Â  Â 3) In some past cases, we have observed that some DX9100s seem to respond more slowly as they age ...
Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  in some of those earlier cases, it has been necessary to increase the N2 response timeout toÂ 
Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  somewhere in the range of 5000-7000ms

Â Â 
Â  Â 4) Mr. Gulotta's email does not mention what Wb/AX version this FX70 is at, but if we knew that, it could

My response to that question is that the BTCVT was originally engineered quite a while ago (say 2005) and was validated with Bluetooth (BT) drivers that were current at that time. Since then, BT drivers have evolved, and we have found that some newer drivers are incompatible with the older BT driver in the BTCVT .. I suspect this is what is going on with Mr Bowen's brand new Dell laptop.Â 

Per solution database article 11309, there is no one simple solution to this. In some cases "...FSC has received reports of some having success in the field by downloading the most recent drivers for a given laptop and working their way backwards through the driver revisions until finding one that works. Others have had success utilizing a third party external Bluetooth USB adapter. The external adapter worked as long as the internal adapter was uninstalled."Â 

Therefore, since Mr Bowen has found an external BT "dongle" that works for him, we would consider that this issue has been successfully addressed. Please correct me if I have misunderstood your situation.Â

JHF email Mar 23/17: "Here are some responses from Tridium regarding your licensing questions ... sorry for taking so long getting these to you:Â 

In any AX or N4 installation, you'll see the total numbers here...Â 
Station > Remote Spy > MetricsÂ 
...which is calculated whenever the Station re-starts.Â 

You usually won't care how these break out per driver, because the N4 license does not break them out, either. It just cares about the total.Â 

BACnet > Export points do not count. This is because the points are already counted under whatever driver _sources_ the data that is exported. Exports have no ProxyExt.Â 

The same exact thing goes for Modbus Slave points. They don't count.Â 

Technically, the points that count toward an N4 license, are all points for which the property ProxyExt.isNull == false."

First he should make sure his html5 user is an admin user, and it would also be a good idea to check the boxes for all the different roles under that user.

For the setpoint editor, make sure it is a writable point. You will also want to map the point down to the priority you are commanding with the setpoint editor. The path would look like this for an override at 8:
station:|slot:/Drivers/JciN2Network/Model1FloatingFCDeHumidComplete/points/CLGUNOCC$2dSP/in8/value

For the other issue, where he can override points in the tree, but not on the graphic, it is probably related to the mapping on the graphic. Generally with N2, you should map down to the "out/value" for things like setpoints.

I also suggest upgrading to Workbench 14.2/Niagara 4.2, as there are a lot of HTML5 fixes in 14.2/4.2.

I draw your attention to note "C" at the bottom of the NADCA Product Specification Standard which reads, "For RoHS (the European Union's Directive on Restriction of Hazardous Substances) compliance, certification of chemical analysis is required to ensure that the "total others" category does not exceed the following weight percent limits: 0.01% cadmium, 0.4% lead, and 0.1% mercury.Â  Hexavalent chromium does not exist in the alloys and therefore meets the 0.1% limit."
Â 
Per the MSDS, the chromium content is 0.01-0.5%.Â  In addition, page #3 of the MSDS stipulates, "CHROMIUM IS PRESENT AT LOW CONCENTRATIONS.Â  CERTAIN CHROMIUM COMPOINDS HAVE BEEN SHOWN TO CAUSE NASAL AND LUNG CANCER BY INHILATION.Â  CHROMIUM AND ITS COMPOINDS ARE LISTED IN THE LATEST ANNUAL REPORT OF CARCINOGENS BY THE NATIONAL TOXICOLOGY PROGRAM (NTP) AND BY THE INTERNATIONAL AGENCY FOR RESEARCH ON CANCER (IARC).
